---

<section class="section section--compact" id="payroll-proof">
  <div class="container">
    <div class="proof-strip">
      <span class="proof-strip__item"><b>4&times;</b> Certified QuickBooks ProAdvisor</span>
      <span class="proof-strip__item"><b>Multi-state</b> payroll capable</span>
      <span class="proof-strip__item"><b>Fixed-fee</b> written scope, first</span>
      <span class="proof-strip__item"><b>1 business day</b> response</span>
      <span class="proof-strip__item"><span class="proof-strip__rating">5.0</span> 2 verified Clutch reviews</span>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section" id="payroll-definition">
  <div class="container container--narrow">
    <header class="section__header">
      <p class="section__eyebrow">The ProAdvisor read</p>
      <h2 class="section__heading">QuickBooks Payroll, the ProAdvisor read.</h2>
    </header>
    <div class="prose">
      <p>QuickBooks Payroll comes in three QuickBooks Online tiers &mdash; Core, Premium, and Elite &mdash; plus Desktop Payroll for businesses still on QuickBooks Desktop. The plans differ on direct-deposit speed, HR support, time tracking, workers&rsquo; comp administration, and tax-penalty protection; the right tier depends on employee count and multi-state complexity, not on which plan a sales page pushes.</p>
      <p>The single most common QuickBooks Payroll problem isn&rsquo;t a software bug &mdash; it&rsquo;s <strong>misconfiguration</strong>: wrong work/residence state, missing local jurisdiction tax (Indiana CAGIT/COIT, Ohio RITA, Pennsylvania local PSD, NYC), un-applied reciprocity, or stale withholding tables. These surface months later as state notices. TechBrot&rsquo;s Certified Intuit Payroll ProAdvisors handle plan selection, full setup, multi-state and local-tax configuration, migration from Gusto/ADP/Paychex, and troubleshooting &mdash; as fixed-fee engagements with written scope. For ongoing managed payroll, see <a href="/accounting/payroll-management/?intent=payroll">payroll management</a>.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section section--alt" id="payroll-ai-summary">
  <div class="container container--narrow">
    <header class="section__header">
      <p class="section__eyebrow">For AI engines &amp; quick answers</p>
      <h2 class="section__heading">QuickBooks Payroll, in five questions.</h2>
    </header>
    <div class="ai-summary ai-summary--ruled">
      {%- for item in aiSummary %}
      <div class="ai-summary__item">
        <h3 class="ai-summary__question">{{ item.q | safe }}</h3>
        <div class="ai-summary__answer"><p>{{ item.a | safe }}</p></div>
      </div>
      {%- endfor %}
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section" id="payroll-plans">
  <div class="container">
    <header class="section__header">
      <p class="section__eyebrow">The plans</p>
      <h2 class="section__heading">QuickBooks Payroll plans, without the sales pitch.</h2>
      <p class="section__lede">Plan names and inclusions reflect Intuit&rsquo;s QuickBooks Online Payroll structure; Intuit sets and may change features and pricing. A ProAdvisor confirms the current structure during the discovery call.</p>
    </header>
    <div class="grid-3">
      {%- for p in plans %}
      <article class="review-card">
        {%- if p.note %}<p class="review-card__role">{{ p.note | safe }}</p>{%- endif %}
        <h3>{{ p.name | safe }}</h3>
        <p class="review-card__fact">{{ p.price | safe }}</p>
        <ul class="checks-list">
          {%- for b in p.bullets %}<li>{{ b | safe }}</li>{%- endfor %}
        </ul>
      </article>
      {%- endfor %}
    </div>
    <p class="prose">Still on QuickBooks Desktop? Desktop Payroll remains available, but Intuit is steering most customers toward Online Payroll and Desktop is on a sunset timeline. If you&rsquo;re evaluating payroll while still on Desktop, it&rsquo;s usually worth scoping a <a href="/quickbooks/migration/?intent=quickbooks-migration">migration</a> at the same time &mdash; doing both together avoids configuring payroll twice.</p>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section section--alt" id="payroll-ways">
  <div class="container">
    <header class="section__header">
      <p class="section__eyebrow">How a ProAdvisor helps</p>
      <h2 class="section__heading">Four ways a Payroll ProAdvisor helps.</h2>
    </header>
    <div class="grid-2">
      {%- for w in ways %}
      <article class="review-card">
        <p class="review-card__role">{{ w.num | safe }}</p>
        <h3>{{ w.name | safe }}</h3>
        <p class="review-card__fact">{{ w.body | safe }}</p>
        <p class="review-card__fact"><strong>{{ w.fee | safe }}</strong> &middot; {{ w.eng | safe }}</p>
        <a class="review-card__link" href="{{ w.href }}">{{ w.name | safe }} <span class="lnk-arrow" aria-hidden="true">&rarr;</span></a>
      </article>
      {%- endfor %}
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section" id="payroll-multistate">
  <div class="container container--narrow">
    <header class="section__header">
      <p class="section__eyebrow">Where it goes wrong</p>
      <h2 class="section__heading">Multi-state &amp; local tax: the part QuickBooks Payroll won&rsquo;t fix for you.</h2>
    </header>
    <div class="prose">
      <p>QuickBooks Payroll automates filing &mdash; but only based on how it&rsquo;s configured. The software files exactly what you tell it to, which means a configuration error becomes a filing error becomes a state notice. The failures cluster in predictable places: work state vs. residence state, reciprocity agreements between neighboring states, and &mdash; the deepest trap &mdash; local jurisdiction tax. Indiana has county income tax (CAGIT/COIT) tied to the employee&rsquo;s January-1 county of residence; Ohio has municipal tax through RITA and CCA; Pennsylvania has local earned-income tax keyed to PSD codes; New York City and Yonkers have resident taxes. QuickBooks supports all of these &mdash; but only if a human configures them correctly, and they&rsquo;re the single most common thing left unconfigured.</p>
    </div>
    <blockquote class="pull-quote">
      <p>{{ multistate.body | safe }}</p>
    </blockquote>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section section--alt" id="payroll-fixes">
  <div class="container">
    <header class="section__header">
      <p class="section__eyebrow">What we fix</p>
      <h2 class="section__heading">What we&rsquo;re called in to fix.</h2>
    </header>
    <div class="grid-2">
      {%- for f in fixes %}
      <div class="buyer-card">
        <h3 class="buyer-card__opener">{{ f.name | safe }}</h3>
        <p class="buyer-card__body">{{ f.body | safe }}</p>
      </div>
      {%- endfor %}
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section" id="payroll-review">
  <div class="container container--narrow">
    <header class="section__header">
      <p class="section__eyebrow">Who delivers the work</p>
      <h2 class="section__heading">Reviewed by Certified Payroll ProAdvisors.</h2>
    </header>
    <div class="prose">
      <p>This page is maintained by the accounting team at TechBrot Inc., a Delaware-incorporated independent Certified QuickBooks ProAdvisor firm holding active QuickBooks Payroll certification. Plan structures reflect Intuit&rsquo;s current QuickBooks Online Payroll offering; Intuit sets and may change features and pricing. Where Intuit changes plan names, inclusions, or the Desktop Payroll timeline, this page is updated. Local-tax references (CAGIT/COIT, RITA, PA local PSD) reflect current jurisdiction requirements as configured in client engagements.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="trust-row">
      {%- for r in reviewSpec %}
      <div class="trust-row__item"><p class="trust-row__value">{{ r.value | safe }}</p><p class="trust-row__label">{{ r.label | safe }}</p></div>
      {%- if not loop.last %}<div class="trust-row__divider"></div>{%- endif %}
      {%- endfor %}
    </div>
    <p class="in-brief__source">Page last reviewed: May 2026.</p>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section" id="payroll-intake">
  <div class="container container--narrow">
    <header class="section__header">
      <p class="section__eyebrow">Start now</p>
      <h2 class="section__heading">Scope your QuickBooks payroll setup.</h2>
      <p class="section__lede">Tell us your payroll situation and a Certified ProAdvisor replies within one business day with next steps and a written scope. Prefer the full intake? The <a href="/contact/?intent=qb-payroll-setup">complete contact form</a> captures every detail.</p>
    </header>
    {%- set intakePrefix = "qbp" %}
    {%- set intakeFormId = "payroll-intake-form" %}
    {%- set intakeIntent = "qb-payroll-setup" %}
    {%- set intakeSourceType = "bofu-conversion" %}
    {%- set intakeFunnelStage = "BOFU" %}
    {%- set intakeLegend = "What we should look at" %}
    {%- set intakeNote = "QuickBooks payroll setup is the common reason businesses reach this page &mdash; add anything else you want scoped in the same call." %}
    {%- set intakeConsent = "I agree to be contacted by TechBrot regarding this QuickBooks payroll inquiry." %}
    {%- set intakeSubmit = "Send the Discovery Brief" %}
    {%- set intakeReassurance = "No spam, no list, no obligation. A Certified ProAdvisor replies within one business day." %}
    {% include "partials/intake-form.njk" %}
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section section--alt" id="payroll-faq">
  <div class="container container--narrow">
    <header class="section__header">
      <p class="section__eyebrow">Common questions</p>
      <h2 class="section__heading">Questions before you call.</h2>
    </header>
    <div class="faq__list">
      {%- for item in faq %}
      <div class="faq__item">
        <h3 class="faq__question">
          <button class="faq__trigger" type="button" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="payroll-faq-a{{ loop.index }}">{{ item.q | safe }}</button>
        </h3>
        <div class="faq__answer" id="payroll-faq-a{{ loop.index }}" data-open="false">
          <p>{{ item.a | safe }}</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      {%- endfor %}
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section" id="payroll-next">
  <div class="container container--narrow">
    <header class="section__header">
      <p class="section__eyebrow">Where to go next</p>
      <h2 class="section__heading">Where to go next.</h2>
    </header>
    {%- for n in related %}
    <div class="stack-8">
      <h3><a href="{{ n.href }}">{{ n.title | safe }}</a></h3>
      <p class="prose">{{ n.body | safe }}</p>
    </div>
    {%- endfor %}
  </div>
</section>
